inference:
You are correct!  There is an error in the solution.  The problem is that the given information doesn't lead to the equation $(1 + r)^2 = r^2 + (2 - r)^2$.  This is because $QX$ and $QY$ are not the legs of a right triangle with $QO$ as the hypotenuse.

Here's a corrected approach:

[asy]
size(250);
pair A, B, C, P, Q, R, S, O, X, Y;
R=(0,0);
Q=(-2,0);
S=(2,0);
P=(1,1.732);
B=(-5.73,-1);
C=(3.732,-1);
A=(1.366,3.098);
O=(0,r);
X=(1-r,1.732-r);
Y=(-2+r,r);
draw(A--B--C--A);
draw(circle(P, 1));
draw(circle(Q, 1));
draw(circle(O, r));
draw(circle(S, 1));
label("A", A, N);
label("B", B, SW);
label("C", C, SE);
dot(P);
dot(Q);
dot(O);
dot(S);
label("P", P, N);
label("Q", Q, SW);
label("O", O, N);
label("S", S, SE);
label("$X$", X, NW);
label("$Y$", Y, SW);
label("$r$", (O + X)/2, W);
label("$r$", (O + Y)/2, S);
label("$1-r$", (P + X)/2, NW);
label("$1-r$", (Q + Y)/2, SW);
[/asy]

Since the circles with centers $P$ and $Q$ are tangent to the new circle, we have $PO = 1 + r$ and $QO = 1 + r$.  Also, $PQ = 2$.  Since $O$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of segment $PQ$, triangles $POQ$ and $POY$ are congruent.  Therefore, $OY = r$ and $QY = 1$.

By the Pythagorean Theorem on triangle $QOY$,
\[r^2 + 1^2 = (1 + r)^2.\]This simplifies to $r = \frac{1}{2}$, so $a + b + c = 1 + 1 + 2 = \boxed{4}$.

